@Hebrew_Tattoos can be inspired truly by anything. Life, family, friends, a verse, or as it was for @SamCogen, a quote from ‘Pirkei Avot’/ פִּרְקֵי אָבוֹת that holds meaning for him.

The compilation of ethical teachings from Rabbinic Jewish tradition is also called ‘Pirqei Avoth’ or ‘Pirkei Avos’ and translates to English as ‘Chapters of the Fathers’.

Sam mentioned a specific sentence from Pirkei Avot that he wanted to get tattooed: אִם אֵין אֲנִי לִי, מִי לִי. וּכְשֶׁאֲנִי לְעַצְמִי, מָה אֲנִי. וְאִם לֹא עַכְשָׁיו, אֵימָתַי: "If I am not for myself, who will be for me? And being for myself, what am I? And if not now, when?" [Hillel the Elder]

➡️ Swipe to see the first step of bringing this tattoo to life and keep reading to see what Sam wrote: 

"The phrase has a deep meaning to me. The last line (if not now when) is in a song that we played at my summer camp growing up. To me, it means that it's important to be there for each other, and then someone will always be there for you. And then there is no time like the present to make a positive change. I have been thinking about getting it for a while but was hesitant because I didn't know what I wanted it to look like. 

I want it to serve as a reminder (even though I won't be able to see it) to make sure that my life and actions reflect the phrase. And to notice it when I catch a glimpse of it in the mirror and give myself that reminder. I find much of my Jewish identity in music and my song-leading experience at camp, so anyway I can tie that together is best.” 

This artwork was inked beautifully by @RobgreenNYC at @BangBangNYC.

To see more @Hebrew_Tattoos, visit their link in bio.
